Adaptive Cards: The Missing UI Layer for Enterprise Human-in-the-Loop AI-Automation
The problem enterprises keep hitting
Enterprises are rapidly automating workflows using AI, APIs, and event-driven systems.
But the moment automation touches money, people, or compliance, a hard requirement appears:
A human must stay in control.
Traditional solutions fall short:
- Custom portals are slow to build and hard to govern
- Emails are unauditable and easily ignored
- Chatbots without structure are risky
- Full UIs increase cost and security exposure
What’s missing is a lightweight, secure, decision-focused UI that fits naturally into daily work.
That’s exactly where Adaptive Cards come in.
What are Adaptive Cards (in simple terms)
Adaptive Cards are a platform-agnostic UI framework for building rich, interactive cards using JSON. Write once → render everywhere (chat apps, email, dashboards). They’re designed for actions + data, not full pages.
Think: buttons, inputs, facts, approvals, notifications — all packaged as a portable card.
Where Adaptive Cards show up in the real world
- Microsoft Teams
Approvals, ticket updates, incident alerts, workflows Outlook links) - Azure DevOps
Build & release notifications - Power Automate
Human-in-the-loop steps - Bots & chat apps (Teams bots, custom chat UIs, web embeds)
If you’re building enterprise workflows (approvals, ops, finance, GST flows), Adaptive Cards are basically the default UI glue.
You provide:
- JSON schema
- Data
- Actions
The host (Teams, Outlook, Web SDK) controls:
- Styling
- Layout limits
- Security sandbox
They are designed for:
- Displaying structured business data
- Collecting decisions and inputs
- Triggering controlled backend actions
They are not full web pages — and that limitation is their biggest strength.
Card structure
{
"type": "AdaptiveCard",
"version": "1.5",
"body": [],
"actions": []
}
Typical pattern
- Automation runs as far as it safely can
- A policy or risk rule is triggered
- The workflow pauses
- An Adaptive Card is sent to the right approver
- A human decision resumes or compensates the workflow
This pattern is known as human-in-the-loop automation.
Example: Approval-Gated Business Workflow
Imagine a payment process:
- AI gathers context (vendor, invoice, amount)
- Policy detects high-value transaction
- System pauses execution
- Finance approver receives an Adaptive Card in Teams
- Approver clicks Approve or Reject
- Workflow resumes automatically based on that decision
No portals.
No emails.
No ambiguity.
