public void handleApproval(ApprovalPayload payload, UserContext user) {
sagaService.verifyWaiting(payload.getSagaId());
sagaService.recordDecision(payload, user);
eventBus.publish(
new ApprovalGrantedEvent(payload.getSagaId())
);
}
Security & compliance architecture view
Teams UI (Adaptive Card)
→ No logic
→ No secrets
→ No API calls
Backend Control Plane
→ RBAC
→ Policy enforcement
→ Audit logging
Event Backbone
→ Replayable
→ Traceable
→ Reliable
Systems of Record
→ Unchanged
This separation is why Adaptive Cards are audit-friendly by design.
What Adaptive Cards are (and are not)
They are perfect for:
- Approvals
- Exceptions
- Overrides
- Structured data review
- Human confirmations
They are not meant for:
- Dashboards
- Complex data exploration
- Free-form workflows
- Rich custom UI experiences
A good rule of thumb:
If the user needs to decide → Adaptive Card
If the user needs to explore → Web UI
Why security and compliance teams like them
Adaptive Cards create a clean separation of concerns:
This enables:
- Full auditability
- Deterministic behavior
- Clear blast-radius control
- Regulator-friendly designs
Why Adaptive Cards matter now
As enterprises adopt AI:
- Automation will increase
- Risk exposure will increase
- Governance requirements will tighten
Adaptive Cards provide a safe interaction layer where:
- AI accelerates
- Humans decide
- Systems execute
- Auditors can trace everything
They are not just a UI technology —
they are a control mechanism.
Summary
Adaptive Cards are the enterprise-grade human interface for AI-driven systems — enabling speed without sacrificing control.
When designed well, they become:
- Invisible to users
- Reassuring to leadership
- Defensible to auditors
- Scalable for engineering teams
